Council voles to support Piﬂ Times

By Mark Gordon and
Stephanie Wright
The Pitt News

Pitt’s Senate Council voted 32-0 at yester-
day’s meeting on a resolution that will allow
the University Times to continue to be pub-
lished independently.

Senate Council President James Holland
said the newspaper is a valuable resource to
the university community.

‘The University Times, some 25 years in
existence, was created as an independent
paper,” Holland said. “It has journalistic
independence.”

Holland told the council that an individual
was hired by Pitt’s administration to review
how the paper operates.

“Recently, the university hired an outside
consultant. The recommendation seemed to
be headed toward making the University

Times more doctored to the university,”
Holland said.

Council member Philip Wion agreed with
the council’s decision on the vote.

“The University Times is a precious and
unique institution at this university. It is
quite rare in this country to have a college
newspaper of this kind to report fairly and
accurately like [the University Times] does,”
Wion said.

Holland described brieﬂy the history of
the University Tmtes and said that 11 years
ago the staff was cut from ﬁve employees
to only three. Because of those cutbacks, the
paper has had trouble covering all university
events, according to Holland.

“The University Times cannot cover
everything we would like to see covered. It
has a small staff,” Holland said. “We would
like to see the University Times become big-
ger and better and still remain independent.”

The council moved to support the inde-
pendence of the University Times because of
a controversial editorial decision from the
publisher Leon Haley.

Haley pulled a story out of the Sept. 15
issue that would have covered a gay wed-
ding in Heinz Chapel. That decision
prompted some university groups, such as
the Bisexual, Gay and Lesbian Alliance, to
criticize Haley for using censorship.

Senate Council reaffirmed that censorship
is not a part of the newspaper and that it
must be continued to run independently.

“It will be a great loss to change the mis-
sion of the University Times,” Wion said.

Also, the council received copies of
“Toward the 21st Century,” a booklet
explaining academic plans for the future at
Pitt.

