Iraq is back

Sadaam Hussein has once again appeared in the news the
last few days as Iraq has amassed 70-80,000 troops on the
border of Kuwait. The response from Bill Clinton and the
United States has been swift and sure. A 36,000-strong U.S.
ground force is being sent to the Persian Gulf along with
about 550 aircraft. _

The quick and strong action by President Clinton is refresh-
ing. He has long been justly criticized for acting too slowly
and tentatively in international affairs. There is definitely
something to be said for careful analysis of foreign policy. It
is, however, also an arena in constant ﬂux, and he who stands
around may be left out in the cold.

.Unfortunately, while the president deserves praise for his
current action, it makes all the more glaring the general incon-
sistencies in U.S. foreign policy — inconsistencies which
extend far beyond the Clinton administration. With U.S.
troops involved in active intervention in both Haiti and the
Middle East, there has been renewed discussion of the United
States’ policing of the world. The justification given for U.S.
intervention in both of these regions has been the upholding
justice, human rights, freedom and democracy. However, the
most glaring violation of these “freedoms” (with genocide
thrown in for good measure) since World War"II has been
largely ignored by the U.S. and the international community.
We are referring of course to the Bosnian situation, in which
not only has the United States not intervened, but the continu-
ation of the arms embargo has put the Bosnian Muslims at a
decided disadvantage compared to the Serbians, whom the
international community have generally decried.

This raises the question then of what exactly does drive
U.S. foreign policy. The answer sadly enough may be nothing.
While economics plays a large role, that cannot answer the
intervention in Haiti. However, our foreign policy interven-
tion strategy is not based simply on freedom and justice for
all. It is time for the United States to formulate a consistent
foreign policy stance, rather than simply to play politics, both
domestically and abroad, every time a new foreign crisis aris-
es. - ‘

The current Iraqi situation has really been a no—brainer for
