Pr taste displayed by lawyers

ost
o f
the

people of
Pittsburgh,
as well as
this newspa-
 fir, applaud-

    

Colt ed the local
Kathi media for
Metinko their delicate

handling of
the tragedy of Flight 427 a
few weeks ago.

The media received such
commendation because they
are usually perceived as
being after the sensational
and caring little for the feel-
ings and reputations of peo-
ple who get in their way.
Such sensationalism often
involves graphic pictures and
accounts of the news.
Perhaps this is why many of
the local stations have begun
broadcasting “family sensi-
tive” news.

What we are now learning,
however, is that we should
not have feared the news
media. The people we should
have feared are the lawyers.
Recent news accounts reveal
these are the true culprits
who disregard people’s pri-
vacy and feelings.

I don’t mean to say that all
lawyers are like this. After
all, I am among the many
attempting to join the ranks.
However, as the saying goes,
one bad apple spoils the
bushel. And in this case, it is
many more than one.

Lawyers for a long time
now have been trying to
overcome the stereotype of
the sleazing ambulance-
chasing litigator who will
stop at nothing to win. Of
course, winning more for
himself at the end than for
his client.

The Pittsburgh Post-
Gazette_ reported on Oct. 2,
1994, a Houston attorney,
John O’Quinn, has a high-

tech approach to courting _

clients. O’Quinn sent a five-
minute videotape to the
families of the victims of
Flight 427. The video appar-
ently opens with O’Quinn
expressing his heartfelt
condolences to the families.
He then proceeds to try to
convince the families that
they must act now; warning
that USAir already has a
team of attorneys working
on the case. He also includes
video of the wreckage of
the USAir flight which

7 crashed in Charlotte, N.C.,

in July. That flight killed
37 of the passengers on
board.

O’Quinn’s tape concludes
with reproductions of the
newspaper headlines announ-
cing his previous trial suc-
cesses and offering an 800
number for families to call
with no obligation.

Most of the families have
been contacted through the
mail. Many friends and more
removed relatives have been
contacted by firms, at times
even offered bribes, to steer
their grieving families
toward a particular firm.

One relative, a paralegal,
was offered $80,000 if she
would persuade the family to
retain the law firm she
worked at, The Post-Gazette
reported. The paralegal
resigned. Another relative
said she has received letters
from lawyers all over the
country. She even received
letters overnight express
everyday the week after the
tragedy.

Five suits have already
been filed against USAir:
two in Pittsburgh, two in
Chicago, and one in
Cleveland. One relative filed
suit soon after the tragedy,
hoping to avoid the unsolicit-
ed mailings of attorneys
looking for the large settle-
ments. However, she is still
receiving the mailings.

Pennsylvania Rules for

Professional Conduct gov-
erning the behavior of
lawyers practicing in the
Commonwealth prohibit
attorneys from soliciting
perspective clients, like
families of disaster victims,
if the lawyer is not related
or has no prior employment
relationship when a reason
for the soliciting is the
attorney’s financial gain; or

if the physical, mental, or

emotional state of the per-
spective client leaves them
unable to exercise reasonable
judgment in employing a
lawyer.

This should become a uni-
versally accepted standard of
behavior for lawyers. It
seems as though it should be
an obvious standard of con-
duct among caring human
beings.

I think it is a shame that
the state Supreme Court has
to define this conduct as
unacceptable to prevent some
insensitive lawyer from
soliciting these grief-stricken
families.

I understand that this type
of conduct would not enter
the minds of many reputable
and competent attorneys, and
society may never achieve a
time when all lawyers have
more respect for human
beings and their feelings than
for their pocketbooks, but we
can hope.

A local band, The
Affordable Floors in their
song “Nothing Personal”
sing a line that seems
strangely appropriate at this
time. The line goes, “and it
seems a little queer, the only
ones making out here are the
lawyers.” It is a terrible com-
mentary on the tragedy when
we all are sending our
prayers to the families affect-
ed and attorneys send their
brochures instead.

